Since $-1 \le x \le 1,$ there exists an angle $\theta,$ $0^\circ \le \theta \le 180^\circ,$ such that $\cos \theta = x.$  Then $\sqrt{1 - x^2} = \sin \theta.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair O, X, Y, Z;

O = (0,0);
X = (10,0);
Y = (0,3);
Z = 7*dir(40);

draw(O--X--Z--Y--cycle);
